**Abstract**

In this study, the efficiency of three different machine learning classifiers is studied, those being Random Forest, Support Vector Machines running with a linear kernel, and Logistic Regression. These 3 classifiers were tested across 3 datasets which are the Iris dataset, Positive/Negative Sentence Sentiment on IMDB reviews, and the Spam versus Ham email dataset. To test the efficiency of these 3 classifiers, on each dataset the training, test, and validation accuracies were taken multiple times, across 3 different splits of the training and test data: 20% test / 80% training, 50% test / 50% training and 80% test / 20% training. On top of these different partitions, hyperparameters across all three classifiers on each dataset were tested to find the most optimal setting for each dataset. The results show that Logistic regression performed better on the more complex dataset, that being the sentiment analysis, and the SVM kernel performed very consistently when it came to “easier” or simpler datasets such as the Iris or Ham / Spam datasets.

---

**Introduction**

Given the widespread use and popularity of artificial intelligence, large language models, and machine learning, the use of many different machine learning techniques and algorithms are being looked at to provide many users with the best, most accurate, and fastest experience possible. This paper looks at the usage of a linear SVM, logistic regression, and random forests to try and decipher the best use cases, depending on circumstances such as the dataset. 

The datasets chosen for this project are the Iris dataset, a dataset traditionally structured multi-classical with numerical data, Spam versus Ham, which has a large amount of messages deciphered as spam or not, and a dataset consisting of IMDB reviews, labeled as positive or negative sentiments. Because of the different levels of complexity within the datasets, these provide a good benchmark while being binarily featured, allowing us to examine the tradeoffs between runtime, complexity, accuracy, and overall efficiency.

---

**Methods**

This study looks at three different machine learning classifiers, across three different datasets, using 3 different partitions for each on the most optimal hyperparameters.

**Random Forests**: An ensemble learning method combining multiple decision trees. The implementation used here is one implemented by SKLearn, where the hyperparameters n\_estimators, min\_samples\_split, max\_features, and criterion were adjusted. For the simpler datasets, it seemed that most of the default parameters were okay, and anything above 100 n\_estimators did not seem to make a difference.

**SVM with Linear Kernel**: SVM is a powerful algorithm for linear and non-linear classification, with the RBF kernel mapping data to higher-dimensional spaces. In this study, we kept SVM linear, and kept c, our regularization parameter, at 1, as there seemed to be no visible benefit to anything above, and clear negatives to dropping below 1\.

**Logistic Regression**: A probabilistic classifier often employed for binary classification tasks and interpretable models. Hyperparameters for the basic datasets were kept pretty basic, with the c value at 10, and max iterations kept at 500 as anything drastically more or less would reduce the accuracy.

### **Datasets and Preprocessing**

**Spam Versus Ham Dataset**: SMS Spam Collection, or Ham versus Spam, was gathered from the UCI repository, and contains lines that are labelled spam messages(spam) or not(ham). Data was vectorized using TF-IDF representation, however nothing else was changed.

**IMDB Sentiment Dataset**: This dataset was taken from UCI repository Sentiment Labelled Sentences, and was chosen over reviews from amazon and yelp.It contains movie reviews that are labelled either positive or negative. Data was vectorized using TF-IDF representation, however nothing else was changed.

**Iris Dataset**: Taken from the UCI repository, data contains 4 numeric features representing sepal and petal dimensions for flower species. As this study was meant to be done over binary featured sets, we classified labels 0 and 1 as 0 and label 2 as 1\.

### **Experimental Setup**

Each dataset was partitioned into three splits:

1. 20% test / 80% train.  
2. 50% test / 50% train.  
3. 80% test / 20% train.

Additionally, for each training set, a certain amount of data was saved for validation, the percentage being either 20 or 20% .

### **Hyperparameters:**

**Random Forests:** Random forests saw the most hyperparameter change across different datasets, mainly the dataset IMDB sentiment. The number of trees was kept at 100, min\_samples\_split was set to 4, max\_features was set to ‘log2’, and the criterion was changed to ‘entropy’ .For the spam versus ham and iris datasets, everything was kept the same and the number of trees was set to 100, as anything more did not affect much, while anything less ruined accuracies. ![][image1]

**SVM:** Was kept as a linear kernel, parabolic or any other kernels did not do much to help, most of the time reducing all accuracies. The regularization value, c, was kept at 1, anything significantly higher or lower reduced accuracies as well. Everything else was kept default.

![][image2]

**Logistic Regression:** Every hyperparameter was kept default, except for max\_iter, which was changed from 100 to 500, and the c value, which got turned to 10\.

![][image3]

**Analysis:** Across all datasets and classifiers, it is concluded that the less training data that is given to the classifiers will result in a worse test accuracy. We see this decrease in both the test and validation accuracy results. Across the board, the classifiers random forest and SVM consistently give the best results, with SVM having a slight edge over random forest on average. 

When given less than optimal conditions, i.e. less training data, the dataset is what ends up determining which classifier can perform better upon those conditions, as Random forest does the best with 80/20 in Iris, but does the worst with the other two datasets. While logistic regression is not consistently as good as the other classifiers, it holds its own and keeps a decent and consistent accuracy across different partitions. 

---

**Conclusion**

In conclusion, this study highlights the significant impact of dataset characteristics and the partitioning of training versus test data on the performance of machine learning classifiers. Random Forest and SVM consistently demonstrated strong performance, with SVM showing a slight advantage in accuracy across most scenarios. However, the effectiveness of each classifier varied depending on the dataset and the amount of training data available. Logistic Regression, despite being less consistent overall, still performed well on text-heavy datasets like the IMDB Sentiment dataset, showcasing its ability to handle binary classification effectively. These findings show that efficiency does not just come with picking the right classifier, but also tuning datasets and hyperparameters to fit these classifiers.
